The difference in how code appears is due to using different elements to display the code. 

In the Button component, you're using inline `<code>` elements, which are HTML standard elements that apply a monospace font style but don't provide additional formatting or syntax highlighting:

```tsx
<p>
    Vi tilbyr tre varianter <code>primary</code>,
    <code>secondary</code> og <code>tertiary</code> som hver
    har ulik visuell vekt avhengig av konteksten.
</p>
```

In the IconGallery component, you're using standalone `<code>` blocks that aren't wrapped in `<pre>` tags:

```tsx
<code>{`import { IconName } from "@byggforsk/fundament-icons-react";`}</code>
```

To make the code blocks consistent between the components, you should:

1. For inline code snippets (like in the Button component), continue using `<code>` tags.

2. For multi-line code blocks (like in IconGallery), use `<pre>` tags with nested `<code>` tags:

```tsx
<pre>
    <code>{`import { IconName } from "@byggforsk/fundament-icons-react";`}</code>
</pre>
```

Here's how you should update your IconGallery code blocks:

```tsx
<h3>Slik bruker du ikonene</h3>
<p>Importer ikonene du trenger fra vår ikonpakke:</p>

<pre>
    <code>{`import { IconName } from "@byggforsk/fundament-icons-react";`}</code>
</pre>

<p>Bruk ikonet direkte i React komponenter:</p>

<pre>
    <code>{`<IconName size={24} color="#0055ff" />`}</code>
</pre>

<p>Du kan også tilpasse ikonet med standard React props:</p>

<pre>
    <code>{`<IconName
  style={{ width: 32, height: 32, color: "currentColor" }}
  onClick={() => console.log("Ikon klikket")}
  className="min-egen-ikon-klasse"
/>`}</code>
</pre>
```

The `<pre>` tag preserves formatting like whitespace and line breaks, making it appropriate for code blocks, while the nested `<code>` tag applies the code styling. This combination will make your code blocks visually consistent across components.
